-o output format
 wide, given more inforarmation more than 

kubectl get pod airflow-deployment-74df595785-kcqxn
NAME                                  READY   STATUS    RESTARTS   AGE
airflow-deployment-74df595785-kcqxn   1/1     Running   0          17h

kubectl get pod airflow-deployment-74df595785-kcqxn -o wide
NAME                                  READY   STATUS    RESTARTS   AGE   IP            NODE                       NOMINATED NODE   READINESS GATES
airflow-deployment-74df595785-kcqxn   1/1     Running   0          17h   10.254.3.60   worker0.ocp4.ignalina.dk   <none>           <none>


 jsonpath
 https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/jsonpath/
JSONPath template is composed of JSONPath expressions enclosed by curly braces {}. Kubectl uses JSONPath expressions to filter on specific fields in the JSON object and format the output. In addition to the original JSONPath template syntax, the following functions and syntax are valid:

Use double quotes to quote text inside JSONPath expressions.
Use the range, end operators to iterate lists.

To specify json output
 kubectl get pod airflow-deployment-74df595785-kcqxn -o json
{
    "apiVersion": "v1",
    "kind": "Pod",
    "metadata": {
        "annotations": {
        ...
    ...
}

To use jsonpath to filter required fields
kubectl get pod airflow-deployment-74df595785-kcqxn -o jsonpath="{.kind}"
Pod
# kubectl get pod airflow-deployment-74df595785-kcqxn -o jsonpath="{@.kind}"
Pod

> . means path to child item from the current item, in above case, it means the output from kubectl get
it is the same as @. since @ means the current item

 kubectl get pods -o jsonpath="{.items[*].metadata.name}"
 
 selector 
 Used to filter out result by label in the yaml file
 kubectl get pods --selector "app=airflow-server" -o jsonpath={.items[0].metadata.name}

 Combined with other command 
 kubectl exec -it $(kubectl get pods --selector "app=airflow-server" -o jsonpath={.items[0].metadata.name}) /bin/bash

 
 
